explain connection between master and agent for using linux machine , docker , kubernets

Here is a simple, beginner-friendly explanation of how Jenkins Master connects to Agents when those agents are running on:

Linux machines

Docker containers

Kubernetes pods

I will explain from scratch, clearly and step by step.

ğŸ”— 1. Masterâ€“Agent Connection on a Linux Machine

This is the most common and easiest method.

âœ”ï¸ How the connection works:

The Jenkins Master connects to a Linux server (agent) using SSH.

âœ”ï¸ Requirements:

A Linux machine (Ubuntu, CentOS, etc.)

SSH service running

Java installed on the agent

Agent credentials (username/password or SSH key)

âœ”ï¸ Steps (Conceptually):

You add the Linux machine as an agent in Jenkins.

Jenkins Master tries to connect using SSH.

Master sends a small Java program (agent.jar) to the Linux agent.

The Linux agent runs this Java process.

This Java process keeps a connection open with the master.

Master now can send jobs â†’ agent will execute them.

âœ” Simple picture:
+-------------+     SSH      +---------------------+
| Jenkins     | <----------> | Linux Machine Agent |
| Master      |              | (runs agent.jar)    |
+-------------+              +---------------------+

ğŸ”— 2. Masterâ€“Agent Connection Using Docker

Here, the agent is inside a Docker container.

There are two common ways:

Method A â€” Static Docker Agent (Manual Container)

You manually run a Docker container that acts as a permanent Jenkins agent.

âœ” How the connection works:

Jenkins Master connects to the container using SSH or JNLP.

The container must have Java installed.

Container runs agent.jar.

âœ” Example architecture:
+-------------+       SSH/JNLP      +------------------------+
| Jenkins     | <------------------> | Docker Container Agent |
| Master      |                     | (Java + agent.jar)     |
+-------------+                     +------------------------+

Method B â€” Docker Plugin (Dynamic Agents)

This is more powerful.

âœ” How it works:

Jenkins Master has the Docker plugin.

When a job starts, Jenkins automatically launches a new Docker container.

The container becomes an agent (runs agent.jar).

After the job finishes, Jenkins destroys the container.

This creates ephemeral agents (temporary workers).

âœ” Picture:
           (Job starts)
          Jenkins Master
                |
                v
      Launches new Docker container
                |
                v
      Container acts as Jenkins agent
                |
                v
      Job completes â†’ Container deleted

ğŸ”— 3. Masterâ€“Agent Connection Using Kubernetes

This is the most advanced and modern method.

Jenkins runs agents inside Kubernetes pods, dynamically created and destroyed.

âœ” How it works:

Jenkins has the Kubernetes Plugin installed.

Jenkins is connected to a Kubernetes cluster using API credentials.

When a job starts:

Jenkins tells Kubernetes:
â€œCreate a pod for my agentâ€

Kubernetes creates a pod with the required container(s).

Inside the pod, Jenkins runs agent.jar.

The pod performs the build.

After completion, Kubernetes automatically deletes the pod.

âœ” Picture:
+-------------+         Kubernetes API          +-----------------+
| Jenkins     | ------------------------------> | Kubernetes      |
| Master      |                                 | Cluster         |
+-------------+                                 +-----------------+
                                                     |
                               Creates Pod with agent|jar
                                                     |
                                                     v
                                         +--------------------+
                                         | Jenkins Agent Pod  |
                                         | (Temporary worker) |
                                         +--------------------+

âœ” Benefits:

Infinite scaling

On-demand agents

Always clean, fresh pods

Perfect for microservices or cloud-native apps

ğŸ” Summary Table
Agent Type	How Master Connects	Requirements	Behavior
Linux Machine	SSH	Linux + SSH + Java	Permanent agent
Docker (Static)	SSH or JNLP	Docker + Java	Manual container agent
Docker (Dynamic)	Docker Plugin	Docker daemon	Creates temporary containers
Kubernetes Pod	Kubernetes API	K8s cluster + plugin	Auto-create/delete pods
ğŸ¯ Super Simple Summary

On Linux:
Master SSH â†’ Linux â†’ run agent.jar

On Docker:
Master SSH/JNLP â†’ Docker container â†’ run agent.jar
or Jenkins auto-creates containers using Docker plugin

On Kubernetes:
Master â†’ K8s API â†’ create pod â†’ run agent.jar â†’ delete pod after job

