explain about jobs in jenkins from scratch

Here is a simple, beginner-friendly, from-scratch explanation of Jobs in Jenkins:

ğŸ§± What Are Jenkins Jobs? (From Scratch)

Think of Jenkins as a robot that performs tasks for you automatically.
A Job is simply a task that you tell Jenkins to do.

ğŸ‘‰ A job = an instruction you give Jenkins.

For example:

Build a Java project

Run test cases

Deploy code to server

Pull code from GitHub

Run a shell script

Build a Docker image

Run a CI/CD pipeline

Every action Jenkins performs is a job.

ğŸ® Why We Need Jobs?

Without jobs, Jenkins does nothing.

Jobs tell Jenkins:

What to do

When to do it

How to do it

Where to run it (agent)

Jobs are the building blocks of CI/CD.

ğŸ§© Types of Jobs in Jenkins (Explained From Scratch)

Jenkins supports several job types. Here are the main ones:

1ï¸âƒ£ Freestyle Job (Beginner Friendly)

This is the oldest and simplest job type.

You create it by clicking:
New Item â†’ Freestyle Project

What it can do:

Pull code from Git

Run shell or batch commands

Build projects

Run tests

Send notifications

When to use:

Small tasks

Simple builds

Quick automation scripts

Example:

â€œRun this shell script every day at 10 AM.â€

2ï¸âƒ£ Pipeline Job (Modern & Most Important)

A Pipeline job uses a script called Jenkinsfile.

This is used for CI/CD automation.

âœ” More powerful
âœ” Version-controlled
âœ” Supports complex logic
âœ” Runs on Linux, Docker, Kubernetes agents

Example Jenkinsfile:
pipeline {
  agent any
  stages {
    stage('Build') {
      steps {
        echo 'Building...'
      }
    }
  }
}

3ï¸âƒ£ Multibranch Pipeline Job

Used when your repository has multiple branches (dev, test, main).

Jenkins automatically:

Scans branches

Detects Jenkinsfiles

Creates pipeline jobs for each branch

Best for:

GitHub/GitLab repos

Microservices

Large CI/CD setups

4ï¸âƒ£ Folder

Not a job technically, but used to organize jobs.

Example:

Folder: "Frontend"

Subjobs: React pipeline, UI tests, lint checks

5ï¸âƒ£ GitHub Organization Jobs

This scans an entire GitHub organization:

Detects repos

Creates pipelines automatically

Used for large companies.

ğŸ› ï¸ Key Components Inside a Jenkins Job
1. Source Code Management (SCM)

Where Jenkins gets the code from:

GitHub

GitLab

Bitbucket

Example:

https://github.com/myproject.git

2. Build Triggers

When the job should run:

On every Git push

On schedule (cron)

When another job finishes

Manually

3. Build Steps

Actual actions Jenkins performs:

Run shell script

Run Maven

Run npm

Build Docker

Example:

mvn clean install

4. Post-Build Actions

What happens after build:

Email notification

Archive artifacts (jar, war)

Deploy to server

Send Slack message

ğŸ§  How Jenkins Executes a Job (Simple Flow)

You click Build Now (or it runs automatically)

Master assigns the job to an available Agent

Agent:

Creates a workspace

Downloads code

Runs the steps

Agent sends logs & results back

Master shows build status (Success/Failed)

ğŸŸ¢ Job Status Colors
Status	Meaning
âœ” Blue/Green	Success
âŒ Red	Failed
âš  Yellow	Unstable (tests failed)
â™º Grey	Not built
â³ Blue/Progress	Running
ğŸ’¡ Simple Real-Life Example of a Jenkins Job
Task:

Build a Java project every time code changes in GitHub.

Jenkins Job Steps:

Pull code from GitHub

Run Maven build

Run test cases

Archive JAR

Deploy to server

This is a job in Jenkins!

ğŸ‰ Final Summary
Term	Meaning
Job	A task Jenkins performs
Freestyle	Simple job (shell commands)
Pipeline	Scripted CI/CD job (Jenkinsfile)
Multibranch	Auto-detect pipelines for each branch
Build Steps	Commands executed inside job
Post-build	Notify, archive, deploy after build

