explain about jenkins file (pipeline as code) from scratch

Here is a simple, complete, from-scratch explanation of the Jenkinsfile (Pipeline as Code).

Iâ€™ll explain it like you are learning for the first time â€” clear and easy.

ğŸ§± What Is a Jenkinsfile? (From Scratch)

A Jenkinsfile is a text file that contains the pipeline code for Jenkins.

It tells Jenkins:

What steps to run

In what order

Where to run them (agents)

How to build the project

How to test and deploy

Think of it as a recipe for CI/CD.

Just like you write a recipe to bake a cake,
you write a Jenkinsfile to build, test, and deploy software.

ğŸ’¡ Why Do We Need a Jenkinsfile?

Without a Jenkinsfile:

Pipelines must be created manually in Jenkins UI (not good!)

Hard to maintain

Hard to track changes

With a Jenkinsfile, everything is code.

âœ” Version-controlled

Stored inside Git (GitHub/GitLab)

âœ” Reusable

Same file works for other teams

âœ” Transparent

Every developer can see CI/CD steps

âœ” Portable

Works on any Jenkins server

This concept is called:

ğŸš€ Pipeline as Code
ğŸ§© Two Types of Jenkins Pipelines

There are two ways to write a Jenkinsfile:

1ï¸âƒ£ Declarative Pipeline (Recommended)

Simple

Structured

Easy for beginners

Uses fixed syntax

2ï¸âƒ£ Scripted Pipeline

More flexible

Written entirely in Groovy

Used for complex logic

ğŸŸ© Declarative Pipeline â€” Basic Structure

Here is the simplest Jenkinsfile:

pipeline {
    agent any
    stages {
        stage('Build') {
            steps {
                echo 'Building the project...'
            }
        }
        stage('Test') {
            steps {
                echo 'Running tests...'
            }
        }
        stage('Deploy') {
            steps {
                echo 'Deploying application...'
            }
        }
    }
}

ğŸ§  Understanding Each Part
1ï¸âƒ£ pipeline { }

Top-level block â€” starts the pipeline.

2ï¸âƒ£ agent

Where the pipeline runs.

Examples:

Use any available agent:
agent any

Use a specific label (Linux agent):
agent { label 'linux' }

Use Docker container:
agent {
    docker { image 'node:14' }
}

Use Kubernetes pod:
agent { kubernetes { /* pod spec */ } }

3ï¸âƒ£ stages { }

A pipeline has multiple stages.

Each stage is a major step in CI/CD:

Build

Test

Deploy

4ï¸âƒ£ stage('Name') { }

A stage represents a task.

Example:

stage('Build')
stage('Test')
stage('Deploy')

5ï¸âƒ£ steps { }

Inside steps, you write the actual commands.

Example:

Shell commands:
steps {
    sh 'echo Hello'
}

Windows commands:
steps {
    bat 'dir'
}

Maven build:
sh 'mvn clean install'

Running tests:
sh 'pytest'

ğŸ“¦ Real Example Jenkinsfile (Build + Test + Docker Image)
pipeline {
  agent any

  stages {
    stage('Checkout') {
      steps {
        git 'https://github.com/myrepo/app.git'
      }
    }

    stage('Build') {
      steps {
        sh 'mvn clean package'
      }
    }

    stage('Test') {
      steps {
        sh 'mvn test'
      }
    }

