explain webhook from scratch and after that explain step by step setup

Below is a complete, beginner-friendly explanation of webhooks from scratch, followed by a step-by-step setup guide specifically for Jenkins + GitHub webhook (most commonly used in CI/CD).
I will explain as if you are learning it for the first time.

ğŸ§  1. What Is a Webhook? (From Scratch)

Imagine you order food online.

Normal way (Polling):

You keep refreshing the app:
â€œHas my order arrived? Has my order arrived?â€

This is polling â€” your app keeps checking again and again.

Webhook way:

You place the order â†’
The restaurant calls you automatically when the food is out for delivery.

This is webhook â€” instead of checking repeatedly,
the system notifies you automatically when something happens.

ğŸ”” Webhook = Automatic Notification Trigger

It is a way for one application to send data to another automatically when an event happens.

Event happens â†’ webhook sends a message â†’ receiver takes action

ğŸ’¡ Examples of webhook events

When something happens in GitHub:

A commit is pushed

A PR is created

Code is merged

A branch is deleted

GitHub sends a webhook to Jenkins.

ğŸ”§ What the webhook sends:

A webhook sends a HTTP POST message containing:

Who made the commit

Which branch was changed

Repo details

Commit ID

Jenkins receives this and triggers a build.

ğŸ—ï¸ Why Do We Need Webhooks?

Without a webhook:

Jenkins keeps checking GitHub every minute â†’ waste of resources

Slow detection of changes

Delays builds

With webhook:

Instant build trigger

Efficient

Reliable

Modern CI/CD

ğŸ¯ Summary of Webhook in Simple Words
Concept	Meaning
Webhook	Automatic message sent when event happens
Trigger	Commit push or pull request
Sender	GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket
Receiver	Jenkins
Purpose	Auto-start Jenkins build
ğŸŸ© 2. Step-by-Step Setup of GitHub â†’ Jenkins Webhook

We will now set up:

ğŸ“Œ When code is pushed to GitHub â†’
ğŸ“Œ GitHub sends webhook â†’
ğŸ“Œ Jenkins automatically starts the pipeline

ğŸŸ© Prerequisites

Jenkins is running (on server or local)

Jenkins URL is reachable (public or via ngrok)

GitHub repository exists

Jenkins job is created (Freestyle or Pipeline)

ğŸŸ§ Step 1: Enable Webhook Trigger in Jenkins Job
For Freestyle Job:

Go to:
Job â†’ Configure â†’ Build Triggers â†’ Check "GitHub hook trigger for GITScm polling"

âœ” Save

For Pipeline Job:

Use either:

Option A: Declarative Pipeline

Inside Jenkinsfile:

