    triggers {
        githubPush()
    }
    ...
}

Option B: Jenkins UI

Job â†’ Configure â†’ Build Triggers â†’ GitHub hook trigger for SCM polling

âœ” Save

ğŸŸ§ Step 2: Get Jenkins Webhook URL

This URL tells GitHub where to send changes.

Format:

http://YOUR-JENKINS-URL/github-webhook/


Examples:

Local:

http://localhost:8080/github-webhook/


Public (ngrok/production):

http://your-domain.com/github-webhook/

ğŸŸ§ Step 3: Add Webhook in GitHub

Open your GitHub repo

Go to Settings

Click Webhooks

Click Add webhook

Fill details:

Field	Value
Payload URL	http://<jenkins-url>/github-webhook/
Content Type	application/json
Secret	(optional)
Events	Just the push event or â€œSend me everythingâ€

Click Add Webhook

If GitHub shows green tick âœ”, webhook is working.

ğŸŸ§ Step 4: Test the Webhook

Push code to repo:

git add .
git commit -m "test webhook"
git push


If everything is set:

ğŸ‰ Jenkins pipeline starts AUTOMATICALLY
ğŸ‰ No manual trigger required

You can also test webhook directly:

Go to GitHub â†’ Webhooks

Select webhook

Click "Redeliver"

ğŸŸ§ Step 5: View Webhook Logs (Optional)
In GitHub:

Go to Repo â†’ Settings â†’ Webhooks

Select your webhook

Scroll to "Recent Deliveries"

Check:

Request sent?

Response status?

Error message?

In Jenkins:

Open job â†’ Build History â†’ Console Output

ğŸŸ¦ Common Problems & Fixes
âŒ 1. GitHub can't reach Jenkins

Fix: Jenkins must have public access
Use:

Public server

Cloud server

Ngrok tunnel

âŒ 2. Webhook returns 403

Fix: Enable anonymous read for GitHub webhook
OR
Use Jenkins API token in Jenkinsfile

âŒ 3. Pipeline not triggering

Fix:
Check Build Trigger is enabled in Jenkins job
Make sure webhook URL ends with:

/github-webhook/

ğŸ‰ Final Summary
âœ” Webhook = Automatic notification
âœ” GitHub sends POST message to Jenkins
