explain about psot action from scratch 

Here is a simple, beginner-friendly explanation of â€œPost Actionâ€ from scratch, especially in the context of Jenkins and Jenkinsfile.

ğŸ§  What Is â€œPost Actionâ€ in Jenkins? (From Scratch)

Imagine you are baking a cake.

You have steps:

Mix ingredients

Bake in oven

Cool the cake

Now, after baking you might do different things:

If cake is perfect â†’ decorate it

If cake is burnt â†’ throw it

Always â†’ clean the kitchen

These â€œafter baking actionsâ€ are like post actions in Jenkins.

ğŸ”” Post Action = What Jenkins should do AFTER the pipeline finishes

No matter what your pipeline does before (build, test, deploy),
post actions decide what happens at the end.

Post actions can run:

Only if build succeeds

Only if build fails

Only if itâ€™s unstable

Or always, no matter what

ğŸ§© Where Do Post Actions Exist?

There are two places in Jenkins:

1ï¸âƒ£ Post-Build Actions (Freestyle Jobs)

In a Freestyle project, you see this section:

Post-build Actions

This decides what to do after build completes.

Examples:

Send email

Archive artifacts

Publish test results

Deploy to a server

Send Slack notification

2ï¸âƒ£ Post Section (Pipeline â€“ Jenkinsfile)

In a pipeline job, post actions are written inside the post { } block in Jenkinsfile.

Example:

post {
  success {
    echo "Build successful!"
  }
  failure {
    echo "Build failed!"
  }
  always {
    echo "Cleaning workspace..."
  }
}

ğŸŸ© Types of Post Actions in Pipeline

Here are all the main post conditions:

âœ” 1. always

Runs every time, no matter what happened.

Example:

post {
  always {
    echo "This will ALWAYS run"
  }
}


Use case:

Cleanup workspace

Close connections

Stop containers

âœ” 2. success

Runs only when build is successful.

post {
  success {
    echo "Build passed!"
  }
}


Use case:

Send success message

Trigger next job

Deploy to production

âœ” 3. failure

Runs only when pipeline fails.

post {
  failure {
    echo "Build failed!"
  }
}


Use case:

Send error email

Notify team in Slack

Rollback deployment

âœ” 4. unstable

Runs when pipeline is unstable
(for example: test failures).

post {
  unstable {
    echo "Tests failed!"
  }
}

âœ” 5. aborted

Runs when build is canceled manually.

post {
  aborted {
    echo "Build was canceled!"
  }
}

âœ” 6. changed

Runs when build status is different from previous build.

post {
  changed {
    echo "Build result changed"
  }
}


Use case:

Notify only if build transitions from success â†’ fail or fail â†’ success

ğŸ’¡ Why Are Post Actions Important?

Because after the build completes, you often want Jenkins to:

Notify developers

Upload build artifacts

Clean workspace

Deploy software

Close cloud resources

Record logs

Without post actions, a CI/CD pipeline is incomplete.

ğŸ¯ Simple Real-Life Example Jenkinsfile with Post Actions
pipeline {
  agent any
  
  stages {
    stage('Build') {
      steps {
        sh 'echo Building...'
      }
    }
  }
  
  post {
    success {
      echo "Everything completed successfully!"
    }
    failure {
      echo "Build failed! Please check logs."
    }
    always {
      echo "Job finished. Cleaning workspace..."
      cleanWs()
    }
  }
}

ğŸ§  Easy Summary
Post Condition	When It Runs	Purpose
always	Always	Cleanup
success	Build succeeded	Notifications, deployment
failure	Build failed	Error alerts
unstable	Tests failed	QA notifications
aborted	Build canceled	Logging
changed	Result different from previous build	Alert on change

