Difference between post-build actions vs post section

Here is a clear, simple, and from-scratch explanation of the difference between Post-Build Actions (Freestyle Jobs) and the Post Section (Pipeline Jobs) in Jenkins.

ğŸ§  1. First, the Basic Difference
Feature	Post-Build Actions	Post Section
Belongs to	Freestyle Jobs	Pipeline Jobs (Jenkinsfile)
Where defined	Jenkins UI (GUI)	Inside Jenkinsfile as code
Flexibility	Limited	Very flexible
Version Control	âŒ No	âœ” Yes
DevOps/Modern CI/CD	ğŸŸ¡ Basic use	ğŸŸ¢ Recommended / Modern
Trigger conditions	Limited	Many conditions (success, failure, always, unstable, aborted)
ğŸ”¹ 2. What Are Post-Build Actions? (Old Style)

For Freestyle Jobs, Jenkins has a section called:

ğŸ‘‰ Post-Build Actions

This section is configured through Jenkins UI, NOT code.

Examples:

Send email after build

Publish JUnit test results

Deploy artifacts

Upload files somewhere

Archive artifacts

Trigger another job

âŒ Limitations:

No version control (not in Git)

Not portable across Jenkins servers

Hard to maintain in large teams

No advanced logic (if this then that)

ğŸ”¹ 3. What Is the Post Section? (Pipeline Style)

In a Pipeline job, actions after the build are defined in code inside the Jenkinsfile:

post {
    success { echo "Success!" }
    failure { echo "Failed!" }
    always  { echo "Runs always" }
}


This is called the post section.

âœ” Advantages:

Stored in Git (version-controlled)

Very flexible

Supports conditions

Supports any number of tasks

Works with DevOps tools (Docker, Kubernetes, Artifacts, Slack)

Fully scriptable and customizable

ğŸ”„ 4. Conditions Comparison
Condition	Freestyle Post-Build?	Pipeline Post Section?
always	âŒ No	âœ” Yes
success only	âš  Limited	âœ” Yes
failure only	âš  Limited	âœ” Yes
unstable	âŒ No	âœ” Yes
aborted	âŒ No	âœ” Yes
changed	âŒ No	âœ” Yes

Pipeline has more advanced conditional logic.

ğŸ“¦ 5. Practical Example Comparison
ğŸ”µ Example of Freestyle (Post-Build Actions)

You go into Jenkins UI:

GitHub project â†’ Configure â†’ Post-build actions

Add:

â€œPublish JUnit test resultâ€

â€œSend email when build is unstableâ€

Everything is set through clicks only.

ğŸŸ¢ Example of Jenkinsfile (Post Section)
post {
    success {
        echo 'Build succeeded!'
    }
    failure {
        echo 'Build failed!'
    }
    unstable {
        echo 'Some tests failed!'
    }
    always {
        cleanWs()
    }
}


Here:

success â†’ send deployment notification

failure â†’ send failure email

always â†’ clean workspace

All written as Pipeline as Code.

ğŸ”¥ 6. Which Should You Use?
âœ” Use Post-Build Actions when:

Learning basics

Very small/simple jobs

No pipeline or Jenkinsfile involved

âœ” Use Post Section (Jenkinsfile) when:

Doing real CI/CD

Using Docker or Kubernetes

Working with teams

Want version-controlled pipeline

Want flexible conditions

ğŸ’¡ Modern DevOps always uses Pipeline + Post Section.

ğŸ“ 7. Quick Summary Chart
Feature	Post-Build Actions	Jenkinsfile Post Section
Job Type	Freestyle	Pipeline
Defined in	Jenkins UI	Code (Jenkinsfile)
Version Control	âŒ No	âœ” Yes
Maintenance	Hard for big teams	Easy (stored in Git)
Conditions	Very limited	Very powerful
Recommended for	Beginners	CI/CD, DevOps
