explain about variables from scratch 

Here is a clear, beginner-friendly explanation of variables from scratch, with a focus on Jenkins / CI-CD, but starting from the very basics.

ğŸ§  What Is a Variable? (From Scratch)

A variable is a named container used to store a value.

Think of it like a labeled box:

ğŸ“¦ Box name: VERSION
ğŸ“„ Value inside: 1.0

Instead of writing 1.0 everywhere, you just use VERSION.

ğŸ’¡ Why Do We Need Variables?

Without variables:

echo "Deploying version 1.0"


With variables:

VERSION=1.0
echo "Deploying version $VERSION"

Benefits:

Reusability

Easy updates

Cleaner code

Less mistakes

Dynamic pipelines

ğŸŒ Variables in Jenkins (Big Picture)

Jenkins supports multiple types of variables:

Environment variables

User-defined variables

Jenkins built-in variables

Pipeline variables

Parameters (input variables)

Weâ€™ll go step by step.

ğŸŸ© 1. Environment Variables (Basic Level)

Environment variables exist at OS level.

Example (Linux):

export NAME=Jenkins
echo $NAME


In Jenkins, environment variables are automatically available.

ğŸŸ© 2. Jenkins Built-in Variables

Jenkins automatically provides many variables.

Examples:

Variable	Meaning
JOB_NAME	Name of Jenkins job
BUILD_NUMBER	Build number
WORKSPACE	Job workspace path
BUILD_ID	Build ID
BUILD_URL	Jenkins build URL
GIT_BRANCH	Git branch name

Use them like:

echo "Job: ${env.JOB_NAME}"
echo "Build number: ${env.BUILD_NUMBER}"

ğŸŸ© 3. User-Defined Variables (Environment Block)

You define your own variables in a Jenkinsfile.

pipeline {
    agent any

    environment {
        APP_NAME = "myapp"
        VERSION  = "1.0"
    }

    stages {
        stage('Print') {
            steps {
                echo "App: ${env.APP_NAME}"
                echo "Version: ${env.VERSION}"
            }
        }
    }
}


âœ” Available in all stages
âœ” Easy to manage

ğŸŸ© 4. Pipeline Variables (Script Level)

These variables exist inside a script block.

script {
    def message = "Hello Jenkins"
    echo message
}


âš  Scope is limited
âš  Not available outside script block

ğŸŸ© 5. Parameters (Input Variables)

Parameters allow users to pass values when starting a job.

Example:

pipeline {
    agent any

    parameters {
        string(name: 'ENV', defaultValue: 'dev', description: 'Environment')
        booleanParam(name: 'DEPLOY', defaultValue: true)
    }

    stages {
        stage('Deploy') {
            steps {
                echo "Environment: ${params.ENV}"
                echo "Deploy enabled: ${params.DEPLOY}"
            }
        }
    }
}


Used when:

You want user input

Different environments (dev, test, prod)

ğŸŸ© 6. Variables in Shell Commands
sh '''
  echo "Job Name: $JOB_NAME"
  echo "Workspace: $WORKSPACE"
'''


In Linux:

$VAR â†’ shell

${env.VAR} â†’ Jenkins Groovy

ğŸŸ© 7. Variable Scope (Very Important)
Variable Type	Scope
Environment (environment {})	All stages
Parameters	Entire pipeline
Script (def)	Script block only
Built-in Jenkins vars	Everywhere
ğŸ§  Simple Real Example
pipeline {
    agent any

    environment {
        IMAGE = "myapp"
        TAG = "v1"
    }

    stages {
        stage('Build') {
            steps {
                sh 'docker build -t $IMAGE:$TAG .'
            }
        }
    }

    post {
        success {
            echo "Built image ${IMAGE}:${TAG}"
        }
    }
}

ğŸ“Œ Common Mistakes (Important)

âŒ Forgetting env. in Groovy

echo VERSION   âŒ
echo env.VERSION âœ…


âŒ Using def outside script
âŒ Expecting script variables in other stages

ğŸ§¾ Quick Summary Table
Type	Defined Where	Used As
Built-in	Jenkins	env.BUILD_NUMBER
Environment	Jenkinsfile	env.APP_NAME
Parameters	Jenkinsfile	params.ENV
Script	script block	def var
OS env	Agent OS	$VAR
ğŸ¯ Final One-Line Definition

ğŸ‘‰ Variables in Jenkins store values that make pipelines dynamic, reusable, and easy to manage.

