explain parameters from scratch

Here is a clear, beginner-friendly explanation of Parameters from scratch, especially in Jenkins, starting from the absolute basics.

ğŸ§  What Are Parameters? (From Scratch)

A parameter is a value you give to Jenkins at build time.

Think of it like ordering coffee â˜•:

You choose size (small / large)

You choose milk (yes / no)

You choose sugar level

Those choices are parameters.

ğŸ‘‰ In Jenkins, parameters allow you to customize how a job runs.

ğŸ’¡ Why Do We Need Parameters?

Without parameters:

One fixed pipeline

Same environment

Same behavior every time

With parameters:

Same pipeline â†’ different behavior

Run builds for dev / test / prod

Turn features ON or OFF

Select branch, version, or server

ğŸŒ Big Picture: Where Parameters Fit
User â†’ Starts Jenkins Job â†’ Provides Parameters â†’ Pipeline Uses Them


Parameters make pipelines dynamic instead of hard-coded.

ğŸŸ© Types of Parameters in Jenkins (From Scratch)

Jenkins provides multiple parameter types.

1ï¸âƒ£ String Parameter

Used to accept text input.

Example:

parameters {
    string(name: 'ENV', defaultValue: 'dev', description: 'Environment name')
}


Usage:

echo "Deploying to ${params.ENV}"


Use case:

Environment name

Version number

Server name

2ï¸âƒ£ Choice Parameter

Used when user must choose one value from a list.

Example:

parameters {
    choice(name: 'ENV', choices: ['dev', 'test', 'prod'], description: 'Choose environment')
}


Use case:

Select deployment environment

Select branch

3ï¸âƒ£ Boolean Parameter

Used for true / false decisions.

Example:

parameters {
    booleanParam(name: 'DEPLOY', defaultValue: true, description: 'Deploy application?')
}


Usage:

if (params.DEPLOY) {
    echo "Deploying..."
}

4ï¸âƒ£ Text Parameter

Used for multi-line text.

Example:

parameters {
    text(name: 'RELEASE_NOTES', defaultValue: '', description: 'Release notes')
}


Use case:

Release notes

Config blocks

5ï¸âƒ£ Password Parameter

Used for sensitive input.

Example:

parameters {
    password(name: 'DB_PASSWORD', defaultValue: '', description: 'Database password')
}


âš ï¸ Usually replaced by Jenkins Credentials (more secure).

6ï¸âƒ£ File Parameter

Used to upload a file during build.

Example:

parameters {
    file(name: 'CONFIG_FILE', description: 'Upload config file')
}


Use case:

Upload certificates

Upload config files

ğŸŸ© How Parameters Work (Step-by-Step)
Step 1: Define parameters in Jenkinsfile
parameters {
    choice(name: 'ENV', choices: ['dev', 'prod'])
}

Step 2: User clicks Build with Parameters

Jenkins shows input fields.

Step 3: User provides values

Example:

ENV = prod

Step 4: Jenkins starts pipeline

Pipeline accesses values using:

params.ENV

ğŸ§  Parameters vs Variables (Important Difference)
Feature	Parameters	Variables
Provided by	User	Jenkins or pipeline
When set	Before build starts	During execution
Can change per build	âœ” Yes	âŒ Mostly fixed
Access syntax	params.NAME	env.NAME or def
ğŸ§ª Simple Real Example Pipeline Using Parameters
pipeline {
    agent any

    parameters {
        choice(name: 'ENV', choices: ['dev', 'test', 'prod'])
        booleanParam(name: 'DEPLOY', defaultValue: true)
    }

    stages {
        stage('Build') {
            steps {
                echo "Building for ${params.ENV}"
            }
        }

        stage('Deploy') {
            when {
                expression { params.DEPLOY }
            }
            steps {
                echo "Deploying to ${params.ENV}"
            }
        }
    }
}

ğŸš¨ Common Beginner Mistakes

âŒ Using env.PARAM instead of params.PARAM
âŒ Forgetting to click Build with Parameters
âŒ Hard-coding values instead of parameters
âŒ Using password parameters instead of credentials

ğŸ“ Quick Summary
Concept	Meaning
Parameter	User-provided input at build time
Purpose	Make pipeline dynamic
Defined in	Jenkinsfile / Job config
Accessed via	params.PARAM_NAME
Common types	String, Choice, Boolean
ğŸ¯ One-Line Definition

ğŸ‘‰ Parameters allow users to control how a Jenkins job behaves each time it runs.

If you want next, I can explain:

