explain roll back from scratch

Here is a clear, beginner-friendly explanation of Rollback from scratch, explained step by step, with real-world + DevOps + Jenkins context.

ğŸ§  What Is Rollback? (From Scratch)

A rollback means going back to a previous working version of an application, system, or configuration when something goes wrong.

Think of rollback like Undo (Ctrl + Z) âª

New change breaks the system âŒ

Roll back to last stable version âœ…

System works again ğŸ‘

ğŸ’¡ Why Do We Need Rollback?

Without rollback:

A bad deployment can break production

Downtime increases

Users are affected

Fixing issues takes longer

With rollback:

Faster recovery

Less downtime

Safer deployments

Confidence to release frequently

ğŸŒ Where Rollback Is Used

Rollback is used in:

Application deployments

Database changes

Configuration updates

Infrastructure changes

CI/CD pipelines

ğŸ§± Basic Rollback Concept
Version 1 â†’ Working âœ…
Version 2 â†’ Deployed âŒ
Rollback â†’ Version 1 restored âœ…

ğŸŸ© Types of Rollback (From Basics)
1ï¸âƒ£ Application Rollback

Reverting application code to a previous stable version.

Example:

App v1.0 â†’ working

App v1.1 â†’ bug

Rollback â†’ v1.0

2ï¸âƒ£ Configuration Rollback

Undoing wrong config changes.

Example:

Wrong environment variable

Wrong port

Wrong database URL

Rollback restores previous config.

3ï¸âƒ£ Database Rollback

Undo database changes.

Example:

Failed schema update

Bad data migration

Rollback:

Restore DB backup

Run down-migration

4ï¸âƒ£ Infrastructure Rollback

Undo infrastructure changes.

Example:

Bad Terraform apply

Wrong server config

Rollback:

Terraform destroy

Re-apply previous state

ğŸ”„ Rollback in CI/CD (High-Level Flow)
Deploy New Version
        â†“
Health Check / Tests
        â†“
Failure Detected
        â†“
Rollback Triggered
        â†“
Previous Version Restored

ğŸŸ¦ Rollback Strategies (IMPORTANT)
1ï¸âƒ£ Manual Rollback

Rollback triggered by a human.

Example:

Engineer redeploys older version

Pros:

Simple

Cons:

Slow

Error-prone

2ï¸âƒ£ Automated Rollback

Rollback triggered automatically.

Example:

Health check fails

Pipeline auto-rolls back

Pros:

Fast

Reliable

Production-safe

3ï¸âƒ£ Blue-Green Rollback

Two environments:

Blue â†’ current

Green â†’ new

If Green fails:

Switch traffic back to Blue

âœ” Instant rollback
âœ” Zero downtime

4ï¸âƒ£ Canary Rollback

Release to small % of users

Monitor metrics

If bad â†’ rollback

âœ” Safe rollout
âœ” Minimal impact

ğŸŸ¨ Rollback in Jenkins (Simple Example)
Scenario:

Deploy Docker image

Roll back if deployment fails

Jenkins Pipeline Example:
pipeline {
    agent any

    environment {
        APP_VERSION = "v2"
        PREV_VERSION = "v1"
    }

    stages {
        stage('Deploy') {
            steps {
                sh 'deploy.sh $APP_VERSION'
            }
        }

        stage('Health Check') {
            steps {
                sh './health_check.sh'
            }
        }
    }

    post {
        failure {
            echo "Deployment failed. Rolling back..."
            sh 'deploy.sh $PREV_VERSION'
        }
    }
}

ğŸ³ Rollback in Docker (From Scratch)
Using tags:
docker run myapp:v1
docker run myapp:v2   # broken
docker run myapp:v1   # rollback

â˜¸ï¸ Rollback in Kubernetes (Very Common)

Kubernetes has built-in rollback support.

Check rollout history:
kubectl rollout history deployment myapp

Rollback:
kubectl rollout undo deployment myapp


Rollback to specific version:

kubectl rollout undo deployment myapp --to-revision=2

ğŸ›¡ï¸ Rollback Best Practices

âœ” Always keep previous artifacts
âœ” Version everything
âœ” Automate rollback
âœ” Use health checks
âœ” Test rollback process
âœ” Monitor after rollback

ğŸ“Š Rollback vs Roll Forward
Rollback	Roll Forward
Go back to old version	Fix and deploy new version
Fast recovery	Slower
Safer in production	Risky if fix fails
ğŸ“ One-Line Summary

ğŸ‘‰ Rollback is the process of reverting a system to a previous stable state after a failure.

ğŸ¯ Interview-Ready Definition

â€œRollback is a controlled mechanism in CI/CD to restore a previous stable version when a deployment or change fails, ensuring system stability and minimal downtime.â€

If you want next, I can explain:
ğŸ”¥ Rollback vs Blue-Green vs Canary
ğŸ”¥ Rollback automation in Jenkins
ğŸ”¥ Rollback in Kubernetes step-by-step
ğŸ”¥ Real-world rollback scenarios

