explain parallel stages in jenkins from scratch 

Here is a clear, beginner-friendly explanation of Parallel Stages in Jenkins from scratch, starting with basics and moving to real CI/CD usage.

ğŸ§  What Are Parallel Stages? (From Scratch)

In Jenkins, parallel stages allow multiple stages to run at the same time instead of one after another.

Think of cooking ğŸ³:

Sequential:
â†’ Boil water
â†’ Cut vegetables
â†’ Cook food

Parallel:
â†’ Boil water and cut vegetables at the same time

ğŸ‘‰ Parallel execution saves time.

ğŸ’¡ Why Do We Need Parallel Stages?

Without parallel stages:

Stages run one by one

Builds are slow

CI pipelines take longer

With parallel stages:

Faster builds

Efficient resource usage

Quick feedback to developers

ğŸŒ Where Parallel Stages Are Used

Running tests (unit, integration, UI)

Building for multiple environments

Deploying to multiple regions

Static code analysis + security scans

ğŸ§± Sequential vs Parallel (Simple View)
Sequential
Build â†’ Test â†’ Deploy

Parallel
        â†’ Unit Tests
Build â†’ â†’ Integration Tests
        â†’ Security Scan

ğŸŸ© Parallel Stages in Jenkins (Declarative Pipeline)

Jenkins supports parallel stages inside a stage block.

Basic Syntax (From Scratch)
pipeline {
    agent any

    stages {
        stage('Tests') {
            parallel {
                stage('Unit Tests') {
                    steps {
                        echo 'Running unit tests'
                    }
                }
                stage('Integration Tests') {
                    steps {
                        echo 'Running integration tests'
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
}


âœ” parallel keyword runs stages simultaneously
âœ” Each stage is independent

ğŸ§ª Real Example: Testing in Parallel
stage('Test') {
    parallel {
        stage('Unit Test') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn test'
            }
        }
        stage('API Test') {
            steps {
                sh 'newman run api-tests.json'
            }
        }
        stage('UI Test') {
            steps {
                sh 'npm run ui-test'
            }
        }
    }
}

â±ï¸ Time Comparison
Approach	Time Taken
Sequential	30 minutes
Parallel	10 minutes
ğŸ–¥ï¸ Parallel Stages with Different Agents

Each parallel stage can run on different machines.

parallel {
    stage('Linux') {
        agent { label 'linux' }
        steps {
            sh 'make build'
        }
    }
    stage('Windows') {
        agent { label 'windows' }
        steps {
            bat 'build.bat'
        }
    }
}

ğŸ³ Parallel with Docker Agents
parallel {
    stage('Java') {
        agent {
            docker { image 'maven:3.9' }
        }
        steps {
            sh 'mvn test'
        }
    }
    stage('Node') {
        agent {
            docker { image 'node:18' }
        }
        steps {
            sh 'npm test'
        }
    }
}

ğŸš¦ What Happens If One Parallel Stage Fails?
Default Behavior:

If any one stage fails, the whole pipeline fails

Other running stages may continue or stop depending on config

ğŸŸ¨ Allow One Parallel Stage to Fail (Optional)
stage('Test') {
    parallel {
        stage('Unit Test') {
            steps {
                sh 'exit 0'
            }
        }
        stage('Security Scan') {
            steps {
                sh 'exit 1'
            }
            post {
                failure {
                    echo 'Security scan failed but pipeline continues'
                }
            }
        }
    }
}

âš ï¸ Common Rules & Limitations

âœ” Parallel stages must be inside a stage
âœ” Each parallel branch must have its own stage
âœ” Shared workspace may cause conflicts
âœ” Requires enough executors/agents

ğŸš¨ Common Beginner Mistakes

âŒ Not enough executors â†’ pipeline stuck
âŒ Writing parallel outside stage
âŒ Using same files in parallel (race condition)
âŒ Expecting ordered execution

ğŸ§  Best Practices

âœ” Use parallel for independent tasks
âœ” Separate workspaces if needed
âœ” Combine with post actions
âœ” Monitor executor usage
âœ” Limit parallelism to system capacity

ğŸ“ One-Line Summary

ğŸ‘‰ Parallel stages in Jenkins allow multiple tasks to run at the same time to reduce pipeline execution time.

ğŸ¯ Interview-Ready Answer

â€œParallel stages in Jenkins are used to execute independent tasks simultaneously, improving pipeline speed and efficiency, commonly used for testing and multi-environment builds.â€

