input step in jenkins

Here is a clear, beginner-friendly explanation of the Jenkins input step from scratch, with real examples and best practices.

ğŸ§  What Is the input Step? (From Scratch)

The input step in Jenkins is used to pause a pipeline and wait for human approval or input before continuing.

Think of it like a manual checkpoint âœ‹:

â€œDo you want to continue?â€

ğŸ’¡ Why Do We Need the Input Step?

Without input:

Pipeline runs automatically end-to-end

Risky deployments may go to production accidentally

With input:

Human approval before critical actions

Controlled production deployments

Compliance & audit requirements

ğŸŒ Common Real-World Use Cases

Approval before production deployment

Confirm rollback

Select deployment environment

Approve database changes

Pause pipeline for verification

ğŸ§± Basic Syntax (From Scratch)
input 'Do you want to continue?'


Pipeline stops here until someone clicks:

âœ… Proceed

âŒ Abort

ğŸŸ© Simple Jenkinsfile Example
pipeline {
    agent any

    stages {
        stage('Build') {
            steps {
                echo 'Build completed'
            }
        }

        stage('Approval') {
            steps {
                input 'Approve deployment to production?'
            }
        }

        stage('Deploy') {
            steps {
                echo 'Deploying to production'
            }
        }
    }
}

ğŸ–±ï¸ What Happens in Jenkins UI?

Pipeline pauses

â€œInput requiredâ€ message appears

User clicks Proceed or Abort

Pipeline continues or stops

ğŸŸ¦ Input Step with Parameters (Very Important)

You can collect values from users.

stage('Approval') {
    steps {
        script {
            def userInput = input(
                message: 'Deploy to which environment?',
                parameters: [
                    choice(name: 'ENV', choices: ['dev', 'test', 'prod']),
                    booleanParam(name: 'CONFIRM', defaultValue: false)
                ]
            )
            echo "Environment: ${userInput['ENV']}"
        }
    }
}

ğŸ§  How Input Parameters Work

User selects values

Jenkins stores them

Values are available in the pipeline

ğŸ” Restrict Who Can Approve (Security)
input message: 'Approve deployment?',
      submitter: 'admin,release-manager'


Only specified users can approve.

â±ï¸ Input with Timeout (Best Practice)

Avoid infinite waiting.

timeout(time: 10, unit: 'MINUTES') {
    input 'Approve deployment?'
}


If no response â†’ pipeline fails or moves to post block.

ğŸš¦ Input Step in when vs stage

input must be inside steps

Cannot be used in when

ğŸš¨ Common Beginner Mistakes

âŒ Forgetting timeout â†’ pipeline stuck
âŒ No permission â†’ approval button not visible
âŒ Expecting automation after input
âŒ Using input in non-interactive jobs

ğŸŸ¨ Input Step vs Parameters
Feature	Input Step	Parameters
When provided	During pipeline run	Before build starts
Purpose	Approval / decision	Job configuration
Can pause pipeline	âœ… Yes	âŒ No
ğŸ›¡ï¸ Best Practices

âœ” Use only for critical steps
âœ” Always add timeout
âœ” Restrict submitters
âœ” Log approval decisions
âœ” Avoid overuse

ğŸ“ One-Line Summary

ğŸ‘‰ The Jenkins input step pauses a pipeline and waits for manual approval or user input before continuing.

ğŸ¯ Interview-Ready Answer

â€œThe Jenkins input step is used to introduce manual approval into automated pipelines, commonly before production deployments, ensuring controlled releases.â€

