explain jenkins shared library from scratch

Here is a complete, beginner-friendly explanation of Jenkins Shared Library from scratch, step by step, with concepts â†’ structure â†’ setup â†’ usage â†’ best practices.

ğŸ§  What Is a Jenkins Shared Library? (From Scratch)

A Jenkins Shared Library is a central place to store reusable pipeline code that can be shared across multiple Jenkins pipelines.

Think of it like a common utility folder ğŸ“¦:

Instead of copying the same pipeline code into every Jenkinsfile

You write it once and reuse it everywhere

ğŸ’¡ Why Do We Need Shared Libraries?

Without shared libraries:

Same Jenkinsfile logic copied into many jobs

Hard to maintain

Changes must be done in many places

High chance of errors

With shared libraries:

Reusable pipeline logic

Centralized maintenance

Cleaner Jenkinsfiles

Standardized CI/CD process

ğŸŒ Real-World Example

Imagine:

50 microservices

Each needs: build â†’ test â†’ scan â†’ deploy

âŒ Without shared library
Each Jenkinsfile repeats same logic

âœ… With shared library
Common logic lives in one repo

ğŸ§± Types of Jenkins Shared Libraries

Jenkins supports 3 types of shared libraries:

1ï¸âƒ£ Global Shared Library

Available to all Jenkins jobs

Configured in Jenkins UI

2ï¸âƒ£ Folder-Level Shared Library

Available only to jobs in a folder

3ï¸âƒ£ Inline Shared Library

Defined inside Jenkinsfile (rare)

ğŸ—‚ï¸ Shared Library Folder Structure (VERY IMPORTANT)

A Jenkins shared library must follow a standard structure.

(shared-library-repo)
â”œâ”€â”€ vars/
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ buildApp.groovy
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ deployApp.groovy
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ src/
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ com/company/utils.groovy
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ resources/
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ templates/config.yaml
â”‚
â””â”€â”€ README.md

ğŸ”¹ vars/ (Most Common)

Contains simple reusable steps

Each .groovy file becomes a pipeline step

Example:

// vars/buildApp.groovy
def call() {
    echo "Building application"
}


Usage in Jenkinsfile:

buildApp()

ğŸ”¹ src/

Used for complex logic

Follows Java package structure

Example:

package com.company

class Utils {
    static void sayHello() {
        println "Hello from shared library"
    }
}

ğŸ”¹ resources/

Stores non-Groovy files

YAML, JSON, templates

Access in Jenkinsfile:

libraryResource 'templates/config.yaml'

âš™ï¸ Step-by-Step: Create a Shared Library
Step 1: Create Git Repository

Example:

jenkins-shared-library


Add folder structure:

vars/

src/

resources/

Push to GitHub / GitLab.

Step 2: Configure Shared Library in Jenkins

Go to:

Manage Jenkins â†’ Configure System â†’ Global Pipeline Libraries

Add:

Name â†’ my-shared-lib

Default version â†’ main

Retrieval method â†’ Git

Repository URL â†’ <repo-url>

Save âœ”

Step 3: Use Shared Library in Jenkinsfile
@Library('my-shared-lib') _

pipeline {
    agent any

    stages {
        stage('Build') {
            steps {
                buildApp()
            }
        }
    }
}

ğŸ§ª Shared Library with Parameters
// vars/deployApp.groovy
def call(String env) {
    echo "Deploying to ${env}"
}


Usage:

deployApp('prod')

ğŸ›¡ï¸ Versioned Shared Libraries

You can use specific versions:

@Library('my-shared-lib@v1.2') _


âœ” Safer
âœ” Avoid breaking pipelines

ğŸ§  Shared Library vs Jenkinsfile
Jenkinsfile	Shared Library
Pipeline logic	Reusable logic
Project-specific	Organization-wide
Hard to reuse	Easy to reuse
ğŸš¨ Common Beginner Mistakes

âŒ Wrong folder structure
âŒ Forgetting call() method
âŒ Not using versioning
âŒ Putting everything in Jenkinsfile

ğŸ§° Best Practices

âœ” Keep Jenkinsfile thin
âœ” Move logic to shared library
âœ” Version your library
âœ” Add documentation
âœ” Write unit tests (Jenkins Pipeline Unit)

ğŸ“ One-Line Summary

ğŸ‘‰ Jenkins Shared Library is a reusable, version-controlled repository that centralizes common pipeline logic for multiple Jenkins jobs.

ğŸ¯ Interview-Ready Answer

â€œJenkins Shared Library allows teams to standardize and reuse CI/CD logic across pipelines, reducing duplication and improving maintainability.â€

